Private Synthetic Data with Hierarchical Structure

Terrance Liu
Carnegie Mellon University
Pittsburgh, PA 15213
terrancl@cs.cmu.edu
&Zhiwei Steven Wu
Carnegie Mellon University
Pittsburgh, PA 15213
zstevenwu@cmu.edu
Abstract

We study the problem of differentially private synthetic data generation for hierarchical datasets in which individual data points are grouped together (e.g., people within households). In particular, to measure the similarity between the synthetic dataset and the underlying private one, we frame our objective under the problem of private query release, generating a synthetic dataset that preserves answers for some collection of queries (i.e., statistics like mean aggregate counts). However, while the application of private synthetic data to the problem of query release has been well studied, such research is restricted to non-hierarchical data domains, raising the initial question—what queries are important when considering data of this form? Moreover, it has not yet been established how one can generate synthetic data at both the group and individual-level while capturing such statistics. In light of these challenges, we first formalize the problem of hierarchical query release, in which the goal is to release a collection of statistics for some hierarchical dataset. Specifically, we provide a general set of statistical queries that captures relationships between attributes at both the group and individual-level. Subsequently, we introduce private synthetic data algorithms for hierarchical query release and evaluate them on hierarchical datasets derived from the American Community Survey and Allegheny Family Screening Tool data. Finally, we look to the American Community Survey, whose inherent hierarchical structure gives rise to another set of domain-specific queries that we run experiments with.

1 Introduction

Differential privacy [9] provides rigorous privacy guarantees that center around limiting the influence of any individual data point. As a result, organizations have increasingly adopted differential privacy to release information while protecting individuals’ sensitivite data. The 2020 U.S. Decennial Census, for example, serves as one of the most prominent deployments of differential privacy in recent years [1]. In this work, we study private synthetic data generation for the purpose of preserving a large collection of summary statistics. This task, which is otherwise known as private query release, is one of most fundamental problems in differential privacy and remains a key objective for many organizations like the U.S. Census Bureau. For example, recent work [14, 11, 31, 18, 2, 19, 22] has demonstrated the effectiveness of generating private synthetic data to solve query release; and after announcing plans to incorporate differential privacy into the American Community Survey (ACS) [16], the U.S. Census Bureau declared (albeit informally) that it intended to replace the public ACS release with fully synthetic data [25].

While private synthetic data generation has shown promise with respect to query release, prior work has not studied the setting in which the data exhibits hierarchical structure (i.e., individual data points that are naturally grouped together). In particular, the synthetic data generation process for records at both the group and indivdiual-level has not yet been established in this problem domain. Moreover, although studies based on hierarchical data often look at relationships between individuals across groups (e.g., trends observed between domestic partners), queries in the traditional setting do not describe such statistics. As a result, social scientists have criticized the U.S. Census Bureau’s objective to replace the ACS with synthetic data, arguing that existing methods are unsuitable since they can only capture statistical relationships at the individual-level [15].

Our Contributions. As alluded to by such critiques, private synthetic data generation remains an open problem for hierarchical data within the context of query release. Therefore, the objective of this work is to explore this problem and introduce differentially private algorithms for synthetic data with hierarchical structure. In pursuit of this goal, we make the following contributions:

  1. 1.

    We initiate the study of hierarchical query release, formulating the problem in which the data domain has two levels—denoted as group and individual111In contrast, previous works only consider data domains containing the latter.—in its data hierarchy.

  2. 2.

    We construct a set of queries that describe statistical relationships across group and individual-level attributes, where our goal is to capture how attributes interact both within and between each level.

  3. 3.

    While our formulation of hierarchical data domains naturally lends itself to running synthetic data generation algorithms such as MWEM [14], these algorithms are computationally intractable. Therefore, inspired by methods from Liu et al. [19], we present a practical approach for hierarchical query release that models the data as separate product distributions over group and individual-level attributes. Using this approach, we introduce two methods, HPD-Fixed and HPD-Gen, which we empirically evaluate on hierarchical datasets that we construct from the American Community Survey (ACS)222To allow researchers to reproduce our evaluation datasets, code for preprocessing ACS data derived from IPUMS USA [28] will be made available online. and Allegheny Family Screening Tool (AFST) data.

  4. 4.

    We use the ACS to formulate another set of queries meant to capture relationships between people within households (e.g., the likelihood that an individual with a graduate degree is married to someone who also has a graduate degree). We run additional experiments in this setting.

Related Work. Query release remains as one of the most fundamental problems in differential privacy [4], and over the years, synthetic data generation has become a well studied approach, both from theoretical [27, 13, 14, 12] and practical [11, 31, 2] perspectives. In particular, Liu et al. [19] unify iterative approaches to synthetic data generation for private query release under their framework Adaptive Measurements and concurrently with Aydore et al. [2] propose methods that take advantage of gradient-based optimization. Moreover, Liu et al. [19] demonstrate that the performance of their iterative algorithms can be improved significantly when optimizing over marginal queries, where the ℓ2subscriptℓ2\ell_{2} sensitivity can be bounded for an entire workload of queries. In later work, McKenna et al. [22] also explore this case, presenting an iterative procedure that achieves strong performance while removing the burden of hyperparameter tuning.

Despite this long line of research applying synthetic data to private query release, prior works—including those that have used the ACS itself for empirical evaluation [18, 19]—are limited to the non-hierarchical setting. In addition, we note that there exist other works that do not tackle this specific problem: (1) those studying private query release using "data-independent" mechanisms [17, 20, 21, 24, 10] and (2) those studying synthetic (tabular) data generation for purposes other than query release [32, 34, 33, 3, 23, 26]. However, such works also do not consider hierarchical structure.

3 Hierarchical Query Release

We now formulate the problem of hierarchical query release, in which we construct a set of queries that our synthetic data algorithms will optimize over. Specifically, to construct a set of statistics describing datasets D∈𝒳𝐷𝒳D\in{\mathcal{X}}, we will focus on linear queries, which we define as the following: {definition}[linear query] Given a dataset D𝐷D and predicate function ϕ:𝒳→ℝ:italic-ϕ→𝒳ℝ\phi:{\mathcal{X}}\rightarrow{\mathbb{R}}, a linear query is defined as

For example, the number of males in some dataset can be represented as a linear query with a predicate function ϕ​(x)=𝟙​{x​ is male}italic-ϕ𝑥1𝑥 is male\phi(x)=\mathbbm{1}\left\{x\textrm{ is male}\right\}. Similar to previous work, we will also normalize query answers with respect to a fixed constant N𝑁N, where N𝑁N denotes some overall count such as the size of the dataset D𝐷D (e.g. % males = # males / # people).555In some prior works, a linear query is defined with the normalizing constant included (where N=|D|𝑁𝐷N=|D|).

In the traditional query release setting, it suffices to construct a set of queries counting the number of (individual) rows satisfying linear queries defined by k𝑘k-way predicates. 4 Synthetic data generation for hierarchical data

Having formulated the problem of hierarchical query release, we next introduce a general approach to answering queries privately via synthetic data generation. Given some family of data distributions 𝒟𝒟{\mathcal{D}}, our goal then is to find some synthetic dataset D′∈𝒟superscript𝐷′𝒟D^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{D}} that solves the optimization problem

minD^∈𝒟⁡maxq∈𝒬⁡|q​(D)−q​(D^)|subscript^𝐷𝒟subscript𝑞𝒬𝑞𝐷𝑞^𝐷\displaystyle\min_{\hat{D}\in{\mathcal{D}}}\max_{q\in{\mathcal{Q}}}|q(D)-q(\hat{D})|

One natural approach is construct a probability distribution over all elements in 𝒳𝒳{\mathcal{X}}, and while methods using this form of 𝒟𝒟{\mathcal{D}} have been shown to perform well [13, 14, 29, 11, 18, 19], they are computationally intractable in most settings given that the size of 𝒳𝒳{\mathcal{X}} grows exponentially with the number of attributes. Inspired by methods introduced in Liu et al. [19], we demonstrate that an alternative solution is to represent 𝒟𝒟{\mathcal{D}} as a mixture of product distributions over each attribute in ℐℐ{\mathcal{I}} and 𝒢𝒢{\mathcal{G}}. In this way, the computational requirements for methods operating on 𝒟𝒟{\mathcal{D}} scale only linearly with respect to M𝑀M and the number of attributes kGsubscript𝑘𝐺k_{G} and kIsubscript𝑘𝐼k_{I}.

Adaptive Measurements. We consider algorithms under the Adaptive Measurements framework [19], which we provide a brief overview for. Having observed that many synthetic data generation algorithms for private query release share similar iterative procedures, Liu et al. [19] present this unifying framework for such algorithms that can broken down into the following steps at each round t𝑡t: (1) sample privately some query with high error, (2) measure the answer to this query using a differentially private mechanism, and (3) optimize some loss function with respect to measurements from all rounds 1,…,t1…𝑡1,\ldots,t. Moreover, they show that the formulation of algorithms under this framework can then be reduced to selecting 𝒟𝒟{\mathcal{D}} and finding a corresponding loss function ℒℒ{\mathcal{L}}.

We restate Adaptive Measurements in Algorithm 1 using the exponential and Gaussian mechanisms for the sample and measure steps respectively. We also note that in our algorithms, we will run these mechanisms under the assumption that all queries q∈𝒬𝑞𝒬q\in{\mathcal{Q}} have ℓ1subscriptℓ1\ell_{1}-sensitivity equal to maxq∈𝒬⁡Δ1​(q)subscript𝑞𝒬subscriptΔ1𝑞\max_{q\in{\mathcal{Q}}}\Delta_{1}\left(q\right). For example, we have a sensitivity of 1NG1subscript𝑁𝐺\frac{1}{N_{G}} for 𝒬=𝒬G∪𝒬I𝒬subscript𝒬𝐺subscript𝒬𝐼{\mathcal{Q}}={\mathcal{Q}}_{G}\cup{\mathcal{Q}}_{I} (since NG≥NIsubscript𝑁𝐺subscript𝑁𝐼N_{G}\geq N_{I}). Having bounded the sensitivity of the queries, we can now preserve the privacy guarantees of Adaptive Measurements for our hierarchical setting (we provide a proof in Appendix A.1). {theorem} For all δ>0𝛿0\delta>0, there exist parameters ε0,ε1subscript𝜀0subscript𝜀1\varepsilon_{0},\varepsilon_{1} such that when run with the exponential and Gaussian mechanisms using ε0subscript𝜀0\varepsilon_{0} and ε1subscript𝜀1\varepsilon_{1} respectively, algorithms under the Adaptive Measurements framework satisfy (ε,δ)𝜀𝛿\left(\varepsilon,\delta\right)-differential privacy.

4.1 Hierarchical product distributions (HPD)

Our goal is derive a probability distribution from which we sample groups (attributes 𝒢𝒢{\mathcal{G}}) and the individual rows (attributes ℐℐ{\mathcal{I}}) contained in each group. Let P#subscript𝑃#P_{\textrm{\#}} be a distribution over the possible number of individuals in each group, and let P𝒢subscript𝑃𝒢P_{{\mathcal{G}}} be the distribution from which we sample attributes 𝒢𝒢{\mathcal{G}}. In addition, for i∈{1,…,M}𝑖1…𝑀i\in\left\{1,\ldots,M\right\}, let Pℐ,isubscript𝑃ℐ𝑖P_{{\mathcal{I}},i} denote the distribution over attributes ℐℐ{\mathcal{I}} such that for each group, the it​hsuperscript𝑖𝑡ℎi^{th} individual row is sampled from Pℐ,isubscript𝑃ℐ𝑖P_{{\mathcal{I}},i}. In Algorithm 2, we present our two-stage sampling procedure, which can be summarized as the following: (1) sample the group-level attributes and group size m𝑚m, and (2) sample m𝑚m sets of individual-level attributes.

Parameterization. Inspired by Liu et al. [19], we choose to parameterize P𝒢subscript𝑃𝒢P_{{\mathcal{G}}} and Pℐ,isubscript𝑃ℐ𝑖P_{{\mathcal{I}},i} as a uniform mixture of K𝐾K product distributions over each group and individual-level attribute 𝒢isubscript𝒢𝑖{\mathcal{G}}_{i} and ℐjsubscriptℐ𝑗{\mathcal{I}}_{j}. Concretely, our parameterization means that for each of the K𝐾K product distributions, we maintain a distribution over each attribute separately. For example, in the ACS dataset, the attribute ℐj=Sexsubscriptℐ𝑗Sex{\mathcal{I}}_{j}=\textsc{Sex} takes on the values Male and Female, meaning that we maintain a 222-dimensional vector corresponding to probabilities that an individual is male or female.

Mixture of product distributions. One can interpret K𝐾K as some tunable parameter that increases the expressiveness of our probability distribution P𝑃P. When K=1𝐾1K=1, we are limited to a single product distribution, meaning that one must assume in the private dataset that for all groups and the individual rows, attributes are independent. On the opposite side of the spectrum, suppose we let K=NG𝐾subscript𝑁𝐺K=N_{G}. Then any dataset with size NGsubscript𝑁𝐺N_{G} groups can be perfectly captured since each row x∈D𝑥𝐷x\in D can be thought of as a product distribution over point masses. In non-hierarchical settings, Liu et al. [19] show that K𝐾K can be much smaller than |D|𝐷|D| and still achieve strong performance.

Linear number of parameters. We note that the number of parameters grows linearly with the number of attributes kGsubscript𝑘𝐺k_{G} and kIsubscript𝑘𝐼k_{I}. In particular, P𝒢subscript𝑃𝒢P_{{\mathcal{G}}} and Pℐ,isubscript𝑃ℐ𝑖P_{{\mathcal{I}},i} require K×dG′𝐾subscriptsuperscript𝑑′𝐺K\times d^{\prime}_{G} and K×dI′𝐾subscriptsuperscript𝑑′𝐼K\times d^{\prime}_{I} parameters respectively, where dG′=∑i=1kG|𝒢i|subscriptsuperscript𝑑′𝐺superscriptsubscript𝑖1subscript𝑘𝐺subscript𝒢𝑖d^{\prime}_{G}=\sum_{i=1}^{k_{G}}|{\mathcal{G}}_{i}| and dI′=∑j=1kI|ℐj|subscriptsuperscript𝑑′𝐼superscriptsubscript𝑗1subscript𝑘𝐼subscriptℐ𝑗d^{\prime}_{I}=\sum_{j=1}^{k_{I}}|{\mathcal{I}}_{j}|.

Differentiable query answers. An advantage of this representation is that mean aggregate queries can be calculated using basic operations over the probabilities for each attribute 𝒢isubscript𝒢𝑖{\mathcal{G}}_{i} or ℐjsubscriptℐ𝑗{\mathcal{I}}_{j}. Therefore, this formulation makes constructing differentiable functions for each predicate in Table 1 convenient. For example, to calculate that the likelihood P​[ℐSex,j=Male]𝑃delimited-[]subscriptℐSex𝑗MaleP\left[{\mathcal{I}}_{\textsc{Sex},j}=\textsc{Male}\right] that an individual generated from Pℐ,jsubscript𝑃ℐ𝑗P_{{\mathcal{I}},j} is male, one can simply look up the probability in the 222-dimensional vector corresponding to the attribute ℐj=Sexsubscriptℐ𝑗Sex{\mathcal{I}}_{j}=\textsc{Sex}. Similarly, to calculate if there is at least one male, it suffices to calculate the probability that a group (given some size m𝑚m) has no males: 1−∏j=1m(1−P​[ℐSex,j=Male])1superscriptsubscriptproduct𝑗1𝑚1𝑃delimited-[]subscriptℐSex𝑗Male1-\prod_{j=1}^{m}\left(1-P\left[{\mathcal{I}}_{\textsc{Sex},j}=\textsc{Male}\right]\right).

4.2 Methods

For notation purposes, we let 𝐏𝒢∈ℛK×dG′superscript𝐏𝒢superscriptℛ𝐾subscriptsuperscript𝑑′𝐺\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{G}}}\in\mathcal{R}^{K\times d^{\prime}_{G}} be some matrix of probability values such that kt​hsuperscript𝑘𝑡ℎk^{th} row 𝐏kℐ,jsubscriptsuperscript𝐏ℐ𝑗𝑘\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}},j}_{k} is the concatenation of the kgsubscript𝑘𝑔k_{g} probability vectors for attributes in 𝒢𝒢{\mathcal{G}}. We define 𝐏ℐ∈ℛK×dI′superscript𝐏ℐsuperscriptℛ𝐾subscriptsuperscript𝑑′𝐼\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}}\in\mathcal{R}^{K\times d^{\prime}_{I}} and 𝐏#∈ℛK×1superscript𝐏#superscriptℛ𝐾1\mathbf{P}^{\textrm{\#}}\in\mathcal{R}^{K\times 1} similarly for individual-level attributes and the group size m𝑚m. In Figure 1, we provide an example of a row in 𝐏ℐsuperscript𝐏ℐ\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}}.

We now describe two methods that are inspired by the family distributions 𝒟𝒟{\mathcal{D}} used in RAPsoftmax and GEM [19]. The first of which maintains a fixed distribution in which the parameters of our model are exactly the probability vectors making up our K𝐾K product distributions. The second of which employs generative modeling by using some neural network architecture that takes as input randomly sampled Gaussian noise 𝐳𝐳\mathbf{z}. Note that in both cases, we use the softmax function to ensure that these methods output probabilities while still maintaining differentiability.

Fixed distribution modeling (HPD-Fixed). Our first method defines a "model" whose parameters θ𝒢superscript𝜃𝒢\theta^{{\mathcal{G}}}, θℐisuperscript𝜃subscriptℐ𝑖\theta^{{\mathcal{I}}_{i}}, and θ#superscript𝜃#\theta^{\textrm{\#}} are simply the matrices 𝐏𝒢superscript𝐏𝒢\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{G}}}, 𝐏ℐisuperscript𝐏subscriptℐ𝑖\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}_{i}}, and 𝐏#superscript𝐏#\mathbf{P}^{\textrm{\#}} respectively.

Generative modeling (HPD-Gen). Alternatively, we propose using a multi-headed neural network F𝐹F to generate rows from Gaussian noise 𝐳∼𝒩​(0,IK)similar-to𝐳𝒩0subscript𝐼𝐾{\mathbf{z}}\sim{\mathcal{N}}(0,I_{K}). In this case, the output of each head, which we denote by F𝒢​(𝐳)superscript𝐹𝒢𝐳F^{{\mathcal{G}}}({\mathbf{z}}), Fℐi​(𝐳)superscript𝐹subscriptℐ𝑖𝐳F^{{\mathcal{I}}_{i}}({\mathbf{z}}), and F#​(𝐳)superscript𝐹#𝐳F^{\textrm{\#}}({\mathbf{z}}), corresponds to the 𝐏𝒢superscript𝐏𝒢\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{G}}}, 𝐏ℐisuperscript𝐏subscriptℐ𝑖\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}_{i}}, and 𝐏#superscript𝐏#\mathbf{P}^{\textrm{\#}} respectively.

Loss function. Following the Adaptive Measurements framework [19], at each round t𝑡t, we have a set of selected queries Q~1:t={q~1,…,q~t}subscript~𝑄:1𝑡subscript~𝑞1…subscript~𝑞𝑡\tilde{Q}_{1:t}=\left\{\tilde{q}_{1},\ldots,\tilde{q}_{t}\right\} and their noisy measurements M~1:t={m~1,…,m~t}subscript~𝑀:1𝑡subscript~𝑚1…subscript~𝑚𝑡\tilde{M}_{1:t}=\left\{\tilde{m}_{1},\ldots,\tilde{m}_{t}\right\}. Suppose we have some set of probability matrices 𝐏𝒢superscript𝐏𝒢\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{G}}}, 𝐏ℐisuperscript𝐏subscriptℐ𝑖\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}_{i}} for i∈{1,2,…,M}𝑖12…𝑀i\in\left\{1,2,\ldots,M\right\}, and 𝐏#superscript𝐏#\mathbf{P}^{\textrm{\#}} that are obtained via either the fixed distribution or generative modeling methods outlined above. Abusing notation, we use 𝐏𝐏\mathbf{P} to denote the collection of these matrices. Then at each round t𝑡t, we optimize the following differentiable loss function via stochastic gradient descent:

Referring to the query types in Table 1, we have that

5 Experiments

Methods. We evaluate methods that optimize over the two distributional families mentioned in Section 4—namely, modeling a distribution over all elements in 𝒳𝒳{\mathcal{X}} (MWEM) and modeling hierarchical product distributions (HPD-Fixed and HPD-Gen).777We provide more details on these methods in Algorithms 4 and 6 in the appendix.

Datasets. We construct datasets from the following:

American Community Survey (ACS) [28]. We first use the American Community Survey as our main evaluation dataset. The ACS gathers microdata annually and is widely used by various organizations to capture the socioeconomic conditions in the country. Survey responses are collected at the household level, describing the household itself (𝒢𝒢{\mathcal{G}}) and the various individuals (ℐℐ{\mathcal{I}}) residing in each household. We use data (101010 group-level and 111111 individual-level attributes) from 2019 for the state of New York (ACS NY-19) and select households of size M=10𝑀10M=10 or smaller. In total, we have NI=197512subscript𝑁𝐼197512N_{I}=197512 individual rows that comprise NG=87453subscript𝑁𝐺87453N_{G}=87453 groups.

Running MWEM requires a domain size significantly smaller than that of ACS NY-19. Therefore, we create a reduced version (444 group-level and 444 individual-level attributes) of the dataset (ACS (red.) NY-19), where we select households of size M=3𝑀3M=3 or smaller. In addition, we combine categories that attributes take on to reduce the domain size further. The domain size of ACS (red.) NY-19 is 262080262080262080, which is significiantly less than that of ACS NY-19 (d≈7.3×1071𝑑7.3superscript1071d\approx 7.3\times 10^{71}).

Allegheny Family Screening Tool Data (AFST) [30]. We run experiments using child welfare data of incidents located in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania, USA. Having been acquired from the Allegheny County Office of Children, Youth and Families (CYF), this data is used by call-screeners to make decisions about which referrals (i.e., reports of child abuse or neglect) to investigate via an AI-based tool called the Allegheny Family Screening Tool (AFST). We select a subset of columns (555 group-level and 101010 individual-level) from the source dataset where M=10𝑀10M=10. Our groups are the referrals themselves, which are comprised of children involved in such incidents. We will refer to this sample as AFST. In total, AFST has NI=74759subscript𝑁𝐼74759N_{I}=74759 individual rows that comprise NG=20448subscript𝑁𝐺20448N_{G}=20448 groups.

Evaluation Queries. As shown in Section 3, given some set of group and individual-level attributes S=SG∪SI𝑆subscript𝑆𝐺subscript𝑆𝐼S=S_{G}\cup S_{I}, we construct group and individual-level queries 𝒬Gsubscript𝒬𝐺{\mathcal{Q}}_{G} and 𝒬Isubscript𝒬𝐼{\mathcal{Q}}_{I}. We restrict the number of attributes for each query to |S|=3𝑆3|S|=3 and choose all such queries. This query selection scheme results in |𝒬G|=|𝒬I|=1333subscript𝒬𝐺subscript𝒬𝐼1333|{\mathcal{Q}}_{G}|=|{\mathcal{Q}}_{I}|=1333 queries for ACS (red.) NY-19, |𝒬G|=|𝒬I|=526684subscript𝒬𝐺subscript𝒬𝐼526684|{\mathcal{Q}}_{G}|=|{\mathcal{Q}}_{I}|=526684 for ACS NY-19, and |𝒬G|=|𝒬I|=127593subscript𝒬𝐺subscript𝒬𝐼127593|{\mathcal{Q}}_{G}|=|{\mathcal{Q}}_{I}|=127593 for AFST.

6 Case study: Modeling intra-household relationships in the ACS

Table 1 summarizes a general class of group and individual-level queries that are applicable to any hierarchical dataset belonging to 𝒳𝒳{\mathcal{X}}. However, we note that this list is non-exhaustive because of the innumerable ways in which one can ask queries about the composition of each group. Therefore, while we contend that the sets 𝒬Gsubscript𝒬𝐺{\mathcal{Q}}_{G} and 𝒬Isubscript𝒬𝐼{\mathcal{Q}}_{I} serve as a good basis for capturing group and individual-level relationships, there could exist additional queries that are important to specific datasets or problem domains. In particular, one interesting set of statistics that may be useful to measure are those that capture relationships between individuals belonging to the same group. For example, one common analysis employed by social scientists using the ACS involves uncovering statistical trends within spousal relationships with respect to attributes like education and ethnicity.

Consequently, we augment 𝒬𝒬{\mathcal{Q}} for the ACS with an additional individual-level query that takes on the form—"shares a group with another individual row with ℐi=ysubscriptℐ𝑖𝑦{\mathcal{I}}_{i}=y"—for some individual-level attribute ℐisubscriptℐ𝑖{\mathcal{I}}_{i} and target y𝑦y. Furthermore, to focus on spousal and parent-child relationships, we restrict the dataset to only heads of the household and their spouses and children. We then let ϕitalic-ϕ\phi be predicates that identify individuals’ relationships to each other (e.g., spouse/parent/child) plus one or more additional attributes (e.g., sex, age, education, etc.). Taken together, we then have intra-group-relationship predicates such as: "has a spouse/parent/child that is male"

Combined with the predicates found in Table 1, we can construct intra-group-relationship queries 𝒬Rsubscript𝒬𝑅{\mathcal{Q}}_{R}. Suppose we have some set SGsubscript𝑆𝐺S_{G} of group-level attributes and sets SIsubscript𝑆𝐼S_{I} and SI,r​e​lsubscript𝑆𝐼𝑟𝑒𝑙S_{I,rel} of individual-level attributes (where SI,r​e​l≠∅subscript𝑆𝐼𝑟𝑒𝑙S_{I,rel}\neq\emptyset). Like in Section 3 we form singleton predicates from SGsubscript𝑆𝐺S_{G} and SIsubscript𝑆𝐼S_{I} (Table 1). However, in this case, we also add intra-group-relationship predicates formed from attributes in SI,r​e​lsubscript𝑆𝐼𝑟𝑒𝑙S_{I,rel}. For example, letting SG={Urban/rural}subscript𝑆𝐺Urban/ruralS_{G}=\left\{\textsc{Urban/rural}\right\}, SI={Education}subscript𝑆𝐼EducationS_{I}=\left\{\textsc{Education}\right\}, and SI,r​e​l={Employment}subscript𝑆𝐼𝑟𝑒𝑙EmploymentS_{I,rel}=\left\{\textsc{Employment}\right\}, we have queries of the form:

    (𝒬Rsubscript𝒬𝑅{\mathcal{Q}}_{R}) What proportion of individuals who live in an urban area and have a graduate degree are married to an individual who is employed?

Similar to assumptions made in Section 3 for the more general setting, we assume that neighboring datasets D′superscript𝐷′D^{\prime} differ on a single individual while maintaining the overall household count. We also assume that households in D′superscript𝐷′D^{\prime} are always valid. For example, households without a head cannot exist. In Appendix A.3, we describe how the flexibility of HPD allows us to make minor changes tailored to this problem domain. Using this modification, we also define fqsubscript𝑓𝑞f_{q} for q∈𝒬R𝑞subscript𝒬𝑅q\in{\mathcal{Q}}_{R}.

Experiments. To evaluate intra-group-relationship queries 𝒬Rsubscript𝒬𝑅{\mathcal{Q}}_{R}, we create a separate sample from the ACS data, which we denote as ACS (rel.) NY-19. In this case, we restrict individual types (attribute RELATE) to the values Head, Spouse, Child, giving us a maximum group size of M=6𝑀6M=6 (up to 444 children and 111 spouse can exist). In Figure 3, we evaluate HPD-Fixed and HPD-Gen on ACS (rel.) using the sets of queries 𝒬=𝒬R𝒬subscript𝒬𝑅{\mathcal{Q}}={\mathcal{Q}}_{R} (left column) and 𝒬=𝒬G∪𝒬I∪𝒬R𝒬subscript𝒬𝐺subscript𝒬𝐼subscript𝒬𝑅{\mathcal{Q}}={\mathcal{Q}}_{G}\cup{\mathcal{Q}}_{I}\cup{\mathcal{Q}}_{R} (right column). 7 Conclusion

In summary, having formulated the problem of hierarchical query release, we present an approach for generating private synthetic data with hierarchical structure. We then empirically evaluate our methods using a variety of query types and datasets, demonstrating that hierarchical relationships can be preserved using private synthetic data. Going forward, we hope that our work will inspire future research on hierarchical data with respect to both synthetic data and private query release.

Appendix B Experimental Details

We provide additional information related to our empirical evaluation.

B.1 Mean error results

We plot mean error for our experiments presented in Section 5 in Figures 4 and 5. Results with respect to mean error are similar to those with respect to max error. We observe, however, that HPD-Gen outperforms HPD-Fixed on ACS (rel.) when run on 𝒬Rsubscript𝒬𝑅{\mathcal{Q}}_{R} only.

B.2 Data

In Table 3, we list attributes from the ACS and AFST data that we use for our experiments. We obtained the raw data from the IPUMS USA database [ruggles2021ipums]. The AFST data is confidential, and so access to the raw data currently requires signing a data agreement. We obtained permission from the Allegheny County Office of Children, Youth and Families to publish error plots on experiments run on a sample derived from this data. More information about the attributes used for the tool can be found in vaithianathan2017developing.

B.3 Algorithm implementation details

We provide the exact details of our algorithms in the following sections. Hyperparameters can be found in Table 4. All experiments are run using a desktop computer with an Intel® Core™ i5-4690K processor and NVIDIA GeForce GTX 1080 Ti graphics card. Our implementation is derived from https://github.com/terranceliu/dp-query-release [liu2021iterative].

B.3.1 MWEM

We restate MWEM in Algorithm 4, with a slight change to the multiplicative weights update rule—in our case, we rescale fqt​(x)subscript𝑓subscript𝑞𝑡𝑥f_{q_{t}}(x) by a factor of 1M1𝑀\frac{1}{M} (Algorithm 5) when qtsubscript𝑞𝑡q_{t} is an individual-level query so that |fqt|≤1subscript𝑓subscript𝑞𝑡1|f_{q_{t}}|\leq 1. In addition, we add empirical improvements described in liu2021leveraging, which are presented in Algorithm 5.

Note that in general, running MWEM is extremely impractical in the hierarchical setting since |𝒳|𝒳|{\mathcal{X}}| scales exponentially with M𝑀M (in addition to kGsubscript𝑘𝐺k_{G} and kI)k_{I}). For example, in the non-hierarchical setting, the domain size of the 888 attributes used in ACS (red.) NY-19 is only 960960960 (compared to a domain size of 262080262080262080 in our case when M=3𝑀3M=3).

B.3.2 Hierarchical Product Distributions

As noted in Section 4, HPD-Fixed and HPD-Gen share the same training procedure as GEM under the Adaptive Measurements framework. For the readers’ convenience, we include this procedure in Algorithms 6 and 7. We note that in our experiments using HPD-Gen, F𝐹F is a multi-headed MLP with two hidden layers that have residual connections between each.

As presented in Section 4, HPD maintains a separate probability matrix 𝐏ℐ,isuperscript𝐏ℐ𝑖\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}},i} for each possible person in 𝒳𝒳{\mathcal{X}}. However, one can further reduce the computational requirements by reusing some probability matrix 𝐏ℐsuperscript𝐏ℐ\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}} for multiple rows in each group. For example, at the other extreme, one could potentially have just a single matrix 𝐏ℐ,isuperscript𝐏ℐ𝑖\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}},i} for all m𝑚m rows in a group, significantly reducing the number of parameters of the model at the cost of expressivity (i.e., characteristics of individual rows are now completely independent of the group size itself). In our standard experiments, we follow a scheme {1,1,1,2,2,3}111223\left\{1,1,1,2,2,3\right\}, meaning that the first three individuals in a household are sampled from 𝐏ℐ1superscript𝐏subscriptℐ1\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}_{1}}, 𝐏ℐ2superscript𝐏subscriptℐ2\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}_{2}}, and 𝐏ℐ3superscript𝐏subscriptℐ3\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}_{3}} respectively, the next two from 𝐏ℐ4superscript𝐏subscriptℐ4\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}_{4}} etc. Similarly for ACS (rel.), we use a single matrix 𝐏ℐcsuperscript𝐏subscriptℐc\mathbf{P}^{{\mathcal{I}}_{\textrm{c}}} for all Mcsubscript𝑀𝑐M_{c} children (i.e., all children in a household are drawn from the same distribution). For future work, it may be interesting to assess how well this strategy can scale to values of M𝑀M that are several times larger than that of our datasets.

Finally, liu2021iterative show that running their algorithm, GEM, without resampling Gaussian noise 𝐳𝐳\mathbf{z} at each gradient step significantly speeds up training time while not harming performance. However, we find that in this setting, our method HPD-Gen performs much better when the noise is fixed, as shown in Figure 6. Regardless, however, we find that HPD-Fixed performs slightly better.
